U.S. Undersecretary of State for the U.S. Mr. Napper, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for the Republic of Korea and Japan, said on November 27 that he would like Korea to reconsider and return the decision to destroy the Japan-Korea Military Information Comprehensive Protection Agreement (GSOMIA), which expires on November 23 at the Ambassador's residence in Tokyo.
It is unusual for U.S. officials to mention the reconsideration of the GSOMIA destruction.
GSOMIA is the foundation for sharing information on missile launches between Japan, Korea, the United States, and the United States.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework to protect military information in Japan and Korea will collapse.
Napper claimed, "We cannot respond effectively to the crisis without GSOMIA."
"There is time to expire," he urged Korea to return.
