cutting-edge art in the world Okayama Arts Exchange opens in the city center: Sanyo Shimbun Digital|san Digi
Old Uchiyamashita Elementary School
The international art exhibition "Okayama Art Exchange 2019" held every three years in the center of Okayama City (hosted by the Executive Committee of the City and Prefecture) opened on 27th.
Along with the mysterious title "IF THE SNAKE," 18 artists from nine countries enjoy cutting-edge art created by artists from Japan and abroad.
This is the second time since 16 years ago, with French artist Pierre Yuig as artistic director, he has developed works that utilize Okayama's climate and local resources.
About 40 films and three-dimensional works will be shown at 13 locations including the former Uchiyama Shimoko (Marunouchi, Kita Ward, Okayama City) and Tenjinyama Cultural Plaza (Otenjin-cho).
Prior to the opening, there was a small opening ceremony and about 100 people attended.
Mr. Masao Omori, Mayor of the Executive Committee, and Mr. Yasuharu Ishikawa, General Producer of the Executive Committee said, "The work that stimulates intellectual sensibility and stimulates imagination and creativity, will become an exhibition that attracts attention from the world."
The families who visited immediately and the children who studied outside the school were able to see a snake-shaped robot that reacts to the sounds of the surrounding area in the dohyo of the schoolyard, and paraded around the school building, which was transformed into a stage of video works depicting the world 3,000 years later.
I enjoyed the art of the world.
When I was traveling with my father, a first-year high school student in Tokyo (15) said, "It's interesting to see a work that takes advantage of the atmosphere of the old school building and imagines the time it flows into this place."
It is closed on Monday (the next day if it is a national holiday) until November 24.
Hong Kong rally in five years of rain umbrella movement tens of thousands, aiming for a general election | Shizuoka Shimbun at es
Five years have passed since the rain umbrella movement started, and people gathered at the meeting hall on 28th in Hong Kong.
[Collaboration in Hong Kong] On the 28th of five years since the 2014 large-scale demonstration "Rainbow Movement," which sought to democratize Hong Kong's election, tens of thousands of people gathered in a park near the Hong Kong Government Headquarters Building in Admiralty, which had the largest demonstration base.
Some young people occupied the main road around the venue and threw fire bottles into the government building.
While protesting against the amendment to the Fugitives Ordinance continued, the participants renewed their determination to fight until the "real ordinary elections" that were not won at the time were realized.
In June, the protests took place over 112 days, more than 79 days after the rain umbrella movement, and the demands of the protesters expanded to "five major demands" such as electoral reform.
